    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Syracuse N. Y.</placeName>
                <date>August 2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> 1852</date>
            </p>
            <p>My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Several months have now<lb/> passed over since I left your City,
                when<lb/> you promised me, that upon my producing<lb/> such proofs of my innocence
                of the Charges<lb/> laid at my door by the <hi rend="underline">kind prelate</hi>
                <persName>Mr Leeser</persName><lb/> that you among the rest would see that
                justice<lb/> should be tend to me—the necessary <hi rend="underline"
                >Documents</hi><lb/> Testimonials, and satisfactory statements have<lb/> long since
                been forwarded to your excellent<lb/> Minister the <persName>Revd Mr
                    Lyons</persName>—Up to this<lb/> date I have received <hi rend="underline"
                    >no</hi> satisfaction in any<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">shape</hi> or <sic>m<hi rend="underline">an</hi>ner</sic>.
                Determined not to let this<lb/> matter drop into oblivion in justice to my <hi
                    rend="underline">own</hi><lb/> reputation, and <hi rend="underline">that</hi> of
                my family—I think it<lb/> my duty to trace the Cause of the silence of the<lb/>
                folks of <placeName><sic>Charlestone</sic></placeName>! I wish to prevent a
                Suit<lb/> at Law, which I shall be compelled to institute<lb/> unless the
                Congregation of your City will exercise<lb/> their prerogative to be the
                adjudicators in this matter<lb/> between me and <persName>Mr Leeser</persName>. I
                ask it now at<lb/> your hands—I have written a letter on the subject<lb/> to your
                worthy President and other Gentlemen who<lb/> were made parties to the affair—my
                injuries were<lb/> of a two fold nature. Defamation of character<lb/> to myself, and
                a pecuniary injury to my family!<lb/> I have therefore to request the favor at your
                hands<lb/> to see that I receive <hi rend="underline">Justice</hi> in the cause—and
                in<lb/> the Hope of your early Reply—Believe me<lb/> yours faithfully</p>
            <p>
                <persName role="author">H. A. Henry</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <persName>S. Vallentine Esq</persName>
                <lb/>
                <placeName>Charleston<lb/> S. C.</placeName>
            </p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName>S. <sic>Wallentine</sic> Esqr</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <placeName>Charleston S.C.</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Pr favr of</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName>Mr D Jacobs</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Present.</p>
